[8] Myanmar (Naypyidaw)
Date: Fri 9 Jul 2010
Source: Mizzima News [edited]
<http://www.mizzima.com/news/inside-burma/4099-naypyidaw-plague-and-dengue-outbreaks-infect-troops-children.html>


Outbreaks of dengue fever are spreading through military units in
Naypyidaw, the Burmese [Myanmar] military regime's seat of
government, according to a military hospital source.

Infected soldiers were admitted to the new 1000-bed military hospital
in Naypyidaw for treatment. Moreover, dengue fever is spreading among
residents in the capital's neighbouring township of Pyinmana
[Naypyidaw], home to 100 000 people.

"Children under-12 [of soldiers] in these Naypyidaw military units
infected with dengue fever were admitted to the children's hospital,
and the troops infected with dengue and their children over 12 were
admitted here," an officer from the military hospital, who requested
anonymity, told Mizzima. He declined to give further details on the
scale of the epidemic.

According to official government figures released last year [2009],
Naypyidaw, meaning Royal City, is the 3rd largest city in Burma
[Myanmar], with a population of 925 000.

Residents of Yauktharinn, Kanoo, Yanaung (2), and Shwechi wards in
Pyinmana [Naypyidaw] said that dengue fever were spreading in their locality.

Previously, it infected children aged between 5 and 12, but elderly
people were now also being infected.

"Some dengue fever patients visited nearby clinics and could recover
within 1-2 days. Some of them were referred to hospitals," a
brokerage owner in Yaukthuarinn Ward told Mizzima.

The virus that causes dengue fever is carried by mosquitoes. Wet,
humid weather during the monsoon has encouraged breeding of mosquito
larvae in drains, ponds, and garbage dumps, which encouraged the
breeding of flies and mosquitoes and the subsequent spreading of the
virus that causes dengue, Dr Khin Myint Aye said. Dengue spreads
because of our inability to fight the mosquito menace, he said.

Dengue outbreaks are not rare in Burma [Myanmar]. Ministry of Health
announced that 910 people were infected with dengue during the
January-May [2010] period, and 6 of those died from this disease,
which is also known as break-bone fever because of severe pain in the
bones and joints that often characterizes infection.

At least 80 people were infected in Rangoon [Yangon] in the last week
of June [week of 28 Jun 2010], Mizzima reported on [1 Jul 2010].

According to official statistics, 3129 Burmese [Myanmar] people were
infected with dengue last year [2009], and 37 died.

[Byline: Kyaw Kha]

--
Communicated by:
PRO/MBDS
<promed-mbds@promedmail.org>

[The dengue virus spreads through the bite of the infectious female
_Aedes_ mosquito, primarily _Aedes aegypti_, which breeds in
artificial containers and in improperly managed garbage where clean
or clear water accumulates (see <http://www.who.int/csr/disease/dengue/en/>).

According to WHO's Regional Office for South-East Asia (WHO/SEARO)
report available at
<http://www.searo.who.int/EN/Section10/Section332/Section2277_11962.htm>,
in 2005 the total dengue cases reported were 17 454 and 169 deaths in
Myanmar. In 2006, the reported dengue cases and deaths were reduced
as compared to 2005.

According to the situation update of dengue in the SEARO, 2007,
available at
<http://www.searo.who.int/LinkFiles/Dengue_DengueSEAR-07.pdf>, the
total dengue cases and deaths reported between January 2007 and
August 2007 were 9578 cases and 117 deaths. During the same period in
2006, the total dengue cases and deaths reported were 8674 cases and
102 deaths. The case fatality rates were 1.22 and 1.18 in 2007 and
2006, respectively.

In 2007, the states/divisions in Myanmar that reported maximum cases
were Mon, Yangon, Ayayarwaddy, Kayin, Tanintharyi, Rakhine, Mandalay,
Bago(W), Bago(E), Magway, Sagaing, with fewer numbers of cases
reported from other states. Myanmar has peaks in July, as has been
observed between 2004 and 2007.

According to the newswire above, officials stated that there were
3129 cases and 37 deaths in Myanmar due to dengue infection in 2009.
From January 2010 to May 2010, there were 910 cases and 6 deaths of
dengue infection. At least 80 cases were reported in Yangon during
the week of 28 Jun 2010. This brings the total number of cases due to
dengue infection during 1st 6 months of 2010 in Myanmar to at least
990 cases and 6 deaths.

The newswire above mentions outbreaks of dengue fever in military
units in the capital, Naypyidaw. Cases were soldiers and their
children and also residents in the capital's neighbouring townships.
However, the numbers of infected cases were not mentioned in the newswire.

PRO/MBDS would appreciate further information from reliable sources
about the current situation of dengue outbreaks in Myanmar.

For a map of Myanmar with administrative divisions, see
<http://www.un.org/Depts/Cartographic/map/profile/myanmar.pdf>.
For the interactive HealthMap/ProMED-mail map with links to other
recent PRO/MBDS and ProMED-mail postings on Myanmar and neighboring
countries, see <http://healthmap.org/r/01Gd>. - Mod.SCM]
